<br>
I typically kite for a few AE's and wait for snare to break for all MOBs.  Then I round them up and snare again.  The second round snare seems to overcome resists quite well. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=alphie>Alphie</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(1/26/02 2:14:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=264.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> snare</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> &quot;it seems kinda dumb to just stand there and cast snare again if one resists and risk snaring yourself. all I do is simply continue running until I have enough range, snare the resister(s) and then round them up again and snare the all one more time. simple, safe, effective. its not like BoF really takes up all that much mana.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
Well by the time you can quad otters you pretty much have to be min lvl 57.  At that level most people have 100MR or close with standard gear.  I snare myself maybe 1 in 1000 and it's usually just because I forgot to switch my gear up.   Also otters have sow and easily outrun your jboots. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   So in this case it's safer, simpler and more effective to stand in place take a beating or two and channel through a snare. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
